<h2>What is Astronomy? </h2>
<font face="times new roman" size="4">
<p>Astronomy is the study of celestial objects and events that occur outside of Earth's atmosphere. It's a physical science that uses math, physics, and chemistry to explain the universe. <br>

The study of astronomy involves objects like: lanets, moons, stars, galaxies, comets, and exoplanets. It also involves the studies of events like supernovae, gamma ray bursts, and cosmic microwave background radiation.<br><br>

<h3><b>History of Astronomy</b></h3>
<font face="times new roman" size="4">
Astronomy is one of the oldest scientific disciplines that has evolved from the humble beginnings of counting stars and charting constellations with the naked eye to the impressive showcase of humankind's technological capabilities that we see today.  <br>

Early astronomers made observations of the night sky, including the Egyptians, Greeks, Chinese, and Maya.<br>

Despite the progress astronomy has made over millennia, astronomers are still working hard to understand the nature of the universe and humankind's place in it. That question has only gotten more complex as our understanding of the universe grew with our expanding technical capabilities. <br>


